I had been regularly (3-4 days/week) practicing the 30 day "dedicate" journey after doing the 30-day "home" journey since late March 2020 at the start of Covid.  For some reason about a month ago, I just stopped and couldn't seem to fit it into my day or didn't make time to do it, and it's been getting me down.  Today I decided to pick it back up on Day 25 (Alive) where I left off and the 14 minute practice was perfect. I'm feeling calm, relaxed, stretched, and wondering why I stopped because each practice leaves me feeling strong and more in control (at least of what I can control).  Just wanted to say that I'm looking forward to completing the 30-day journey in spite of my hiatus.  Thanks for welcoming me back.

It’s taking me more than three months to finish Dedicate (!) but it never ceases to amaze me that the closing comments in a video made more than a year and a half ago really speak to me on the day in the crazy future I happen to do it. Needed this today:
“I often describe yoga practice as one, of many, but one way to help guide us to find our meaningful contribution to society. And that can be frustrating sometimes because you’re like: ‘I don’t know what to do’ or ‘I don’t know’. And so today’s practice just reminds us that you don’t have to know. Just cultivate a practice of finding what feels good and continuing to follow what makes you feel alive. And surround yourself with people that make you feel alive.”
Namaste 🙏❤🙏

I hurt my lower back yesterday doing yard work. Have no idea was I did, but performus muscle is just firing off pain signals. So this morning it was really really really hard to get to the mat. I was more painful than I expected and there was no way I could do 1 legged downward dog. But I did get through the whole thing only pausing twice so I could catch up. I wish I could say I was healed like magic, that didn't happen. But I do have just a little more mobility. I will see this 151 days odyssey through now that I am this close to the end 2019's 30 Days of Yoga. I guess next up will be Adriene's series on the back?

It's like you knew that this is exactly the session I needed today, but of course you did, you set up the entire program thoughtfully. You guys, I started my at home practice yoga journey with Adriene based on my mental health in mind, and figured that any physical consequence would be a bonus. At the same time I stopped drinking my calories. Ten weeks in, I've lost 13 pounds, loads of physical discomfort and pain, gained peace of mind, flexibility and muscles! I've gained visible muscles! I just wanted to leave this here, because I've seen videos claiming that you can't loose weight with yoga, but I did! Now I'm hopeful I can get back to my healthy weight goal, which is another 15-ish punds. All I did was stop drinking my calories (I could very easily tend to red wine in the evening), and do some Adriene Yoga every day, if I had a super hectic day where I didn't find time during it for a practice, I would do her good night routine in bed, then sleep like a baby. I never starved or suffered.

Today I decided that I (not the dog) needed a training refresher. We sat at a busy shopping center with dogs walking about. I put her on a down/stay and out myself into deep, slow, belly breathing. Dear Adriene, 
Today I did not follow along with your practice. I have you to thank for that. I woke up feeling really motivated to breathe, draw inward and move my body in ways that felt good... just like you've always taught me. So I rolled out my mat, played "Porcelain" by Moby quietly on repeat (this song is Yogi gold) and moved through a completely original practice that I created myself in the moment by flowing into each posture that both challenged me and felt good. All with everything that you've taught me all these years. What I learned today, was that doing this allowed me to connect my body and mind in a way that I've never been able to do while following any of your videos. Thank you for giving me the tools to do this on my own today. I love you, namaste.
